erature. Through a comparative analysis of an extensive corpus of writings by renowned Russian and Jewish thinkers, the book reveals how ideas regarding the need for a national awakening penetrated from Russian to Jewish thought. The Jewish thinkers who embraced these notions adapted them to the reality and experience of Jewish life in Central and Eastern Europe. Likewise, portrayals of an individual’s quest for the authentic and just God in Russian literary works gained purchase in ideological Hebrew literature, where the hero searches for a true path to achieve spiritual, social, and national well-being for the Jewish people. Absorption of ideological influences is a universal phenomenon that is instrumental to progress and cultural development, and it is accepted in Jewish culture as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHebrew literaturey19th centuryxRussian influences. 0aHebrew literaturey20th centuryxRussian influences. 0aIdeology in literature. 0aJewish literaturey19th centuryxRussian influences. 0aJewish literaturey20th centuryxRussian influences. 0aJewszEurope, CentralxIntellectual life. 0aJewszEurope, EasternxIntellectual life. 0aNational characteristics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aHaskala.  aHebrew literature.  aJewish life.  aJewish literature.  aJewish national movement.  aJewish thought.  aRussian literature.  aRussian thought.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/979888719402840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9798887194028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9798887194028/original  a978-3-11-102354-0  Academic S